  "text": "## Apache Flink Windowing API Extension Points\n\n### 1. WindowAssigner Abstract Base Class\n**Location:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/WindowAssigner.java`\n\nThe `WindowAssigner<T, W extends Window>` abstract class is the core extension point for implementing custom window assignment strategies. Developers implementing custom window assigners must extend this class and provide implementations for the following abstract methods:\n\n**Abstract Methods:**\n- `Collection<W> assignWindows(T element, long timestamp, WindowAssignerContext context)` - Assigns zero or more windows to an incoming element based on the element, its timestamp, and the current processing time context.\n- `Trigger<T, W> getDefaultTrigger()` - Returns the default trigger that determines when windows should fire for processing.\n- `TypeSerializer<W> getWindowSerializer(ExecutionConfig executionConfig)` - Provides a serializer for the window type, required for checkpointing and state management.\n- `boolean isEventTime()` - Indicates whether this assigner operates on event time (true) or processing time (false).\n\nThe class also defines the nested abstract class `WindowAssignerContext` with method `long getCurrentProcessingTime()` for context-aware window assignment.\n\n### 2. MergingWindowAssigner for Session-Style Windows\n**Location:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/MergingWindowAssigner.java`\n\nThe `MergingWindowAssigner<T, W extends Window>` class extends `WindowAssigner` to support session windows and other window types that require merging. Developers implementing session-style or merging window assigners must extend this class and implement the additional abstract method:\n\n**Abstract Method:**\n- `void mergeWindows(Collection<W> windows, MergeCallback<W> callback)` - Determines which windows should be merged together and invokes the callback to signal the merge operation.\n\nThe class provides the nested `MergeCallback<W>` interface with method `void merge(Collection<W> toBeMerged, W mergeResult)` for signaling merge results.\n\n### 3. Trigger Lifecycle Methods\n**Location:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/triggers/Trigger.java`\n\nThe `Trigger<T, W extends Window>` abstract class defines the lifecycle hooks for window firing. Developers implementing custom triggers must extend this class and provide implementations for the following abstract lifecycle methods:\n\n**Abstract Lifecycle Methods:**\n- `TriggerResult onElement(T element, long timestamp, W window, TriggerContext ctx)` throws Exception - Called when an element is added to a window pane; determines whether the pane should fire.\n- `TriggerResult onEventTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)` throws Exception - Called when an event-time timer fires; allows time-based triggering.\n- `TriggerResult onProcessingTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)` throws Exception - Called when a processing-time timer fires; enables wall-clock time-based triggering.\n- `void clear(W window, TriggerContext ctx)` throws Exception - Called when a window is purged; should clean up any trigger state and delete registered timers.\n\n**Optional Override Methods (with defaults):**\n- `boolean canMerge()` - Override to return true if the trigger supports state merging for merging window assigners.\n- `void onMerge(W window, OnMergeContext ctx)` throws Exception - Called when windows are merged; must be implemented if canMerge() returns true.\n\n**Nested Context Interfaces:**\n- `TriggerContext` - Provides access to state, watermark, and timer registration methods.\n- `OnMergeContext extends TriggerContext` - Extended context for merge operations with method `void mergePartitionedState(StateDescriptor<S, ?> stateDescriptor)`.\n\n### 4. EventTimeSessionWindows Reference Implementation\n**Location:** `flink-streaming-java/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/EventTimeSessionWindows.java`\n\nThe `EventTimeSessionWindows` class extends `MergingWindowAssigner<Object, TimeWindow>` and provides a concrete reference implementation of a session window assigner. Key implementations:\n\n**Method Implementations:**\n- `Collection<TimeWindow> assignWindows(Object element, long timestamp, WindowAssignerContext context)` - Creates a single `TimeWindow` from the element's timestamp to `timestamp + sessionTimeout`. Returns `Collections.singletonList(new TimeWindow(timestamp, timestamp + sessionTimeout))`.\n- `void mergeWindows(Collection<TimeWindow> windows, MergeCallback<TimeWindow> callback)` - Delegates to the static utility method `TimeWindow.mergeWindows(windows, callback)`, which handles overlapping window detection and merging.\n- `Trigger<Object, TimeWindow> getDefaultTrigger()` - Returns `EventTimeTrigger.create()`, the default trigger for event-time session windows.\n- `TypeSerializer<TimeWindow> getWindowSerializer(ExecutionConfig executionConfig)` - Returns `new TimeWindow.Serializer()` for serialization.\n- `boolean isEventTime()` - Returns true, indicating this assigner operates on event time.\n\n### 5. TimeWindow Class\n**Location:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/windows/TimeWindow.java`\n\nThe `TimeWindow` class extends the abstract `Window` class and represents time intervals used by all time-based window assigners. Key components:\n\n**Constructor:**\n- `TimeWindow(long start, long end)` - Creates a window representing the time interval [start, end).\n\n**Core Methods:**\n- `long getStart()` - Returns the inclusive start timestamp.\n- `long getEnd()` - Returns the exclusive end timestamp.\n- `long maxTimestamp()` - Overrides abstract method from Window; returns `end - 1` (the maximum timestamp belonging to this window).\n\n**Window Utilities:**\n- `boolean intersects(TimeWindow other)` - Checks if this window overlaps with another window.\n- `TimeWindow cover(TimeWindow other)` - Returns a new window that covers both this and the given window.\n- `static void mergeWindows(Collection<TimeWindow> windows, MergeCallback<TimeWindow> callback)` - Static utility method used by merging window assigners to detect and merge overlapping windows. Sorts windows by start time and groups overlapping windows for merging.\n- `static long getWindowStartWithOffset(long timestamp, long offset, long windowSize)` - Utility for computing aligned window boundaries.\n\n### 6. Window Base Class Hierarchy\n**Location:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/windows/Window.java`\n\nThe abstract `Window` class is the top-level abstraction for all window types in Flink. It defines:\n\n**Abstract Method:**\n- `long maxTimestamp()` - Must be implemented by all window subclasses to return the maximum timestamp that belongs to the window. This is used by the framework to determine when all elements for a window have arrived.\n\n## Implementation Chain for Custom Window Assigners\n\nA developer implementing a custom window assigner would follow this extension chain:\n\n1. Extend `WindowAssigner<T, W>` (or `MergingWindowAssigner<T, W>` for session-style windows)\n2. Implement `assignWindows()` to return instances of a custom Window subclass or `TimeWindow`\n3. The returned windows extend `Window` and must implement `maxTimestamp()`\n4. Provide a default `Trigger<T, W>` that extends `Trigger` and implements the lifecycle methods: `onElement`, `onEventTime`, `onProcessingTime`, `clear`, and optionally `canMerge` and `onMerge`\n5. Provide `getWindowSerializer()` for state serialization\n6. Set `isEventTime()` based on whether the assigner uses event or processing time\n\nThe `EventTimeSessionWindows` implementation demonstrates this pattern by returning `TimeWindow` instances through `assignWindows()`, delegating window merging to `TimeWindow.mergeWindows()`, and providing `EventTimeTrigger` as the default trigger."
}

